States Navy}}<br>{{flag|United States Air Force}}\n|serviceyears = 1998\u20132007 (Active)<br>2010\u20132015 (Reserve)<br>2015\u2013present (Air National Guard)\n|rank         = [[File:US-O4 insignia.svg|15px]] [[Lieutenant commander (United States)|Lieutenant Commander]] (Active)<br>[[File:US-O4 insignia.svg|15px]] [[Lieutenant commander (United States)|Lieutenant Commander]] (Reserve)<br>[[File:US-O4 insignia.svg|15px]] [[Major (United States)|Major]] (Air National Guard)\n|unit         = [[Oklahoma Air National Guard]]\n|battles      = [[War in Afghanistan]]\n|mawards      = {{collapsible list\n |titlestyle= background:transparent;text-align:left;font-weight:normal;\n |title= See list\n|[[Commendation Medal|Navy and Marine Corps Commendation Medal]] (2) (w/ [[\"V\" device]])<br>[[Achievement Medal|Navy and Marine Corps Achievement Medal]] <br>[[Navy Unit Commendation]]<br>[[Navy E Ribbon]]<br>[[Global War on Terrorism Expeditionary Medal]]<br>[[Global War on Terrorism Service Medal]]<br>[[National Defense Service Medal]]<br>[[Armed Forces Expeditionary Medal]]<br>[[Sea Service Ribbon|Sea Service Deployment Ribbon]]<br>[[Marksmanship Medal|Expert Pistol Medal]]}}\n}}\n'''James Frederick Bridenstine''' (born June 15, 1975) is an American politician and the administrator of the [[National Aeronautics and Space Administration]]. Bridenstine served as the [[United States House of Representatives|United States Representative]] for [[Oklahoma's 1st congressional district]], based in [[Tulsa]] from January 3, 2013 to April 23, 2018. He is a member of the [[Republican Party (US)|Republican Party]].\n\nOn September 1, 2017, [[President of the United States|President]] [[Donald Trump]] nominated Bridenstine to be the [[List of Administrators and Deputy Administrators of NASA|Administrator]] of the [[National Aeronautics and Space Administration]] (NASA); he was confirmed by the [[United States Senate|U.S. Senate]] on April 19, 2018. Bridenstine has served on the [[United States House Committee on Science, Space and Technology|Committee on Science, Space and Technology]] during his time in Congress. He is the first elected official to serve as NASA Administrator.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/19/science/jim-bridenstine-nasa.html|title=Trump's NASA Nominee, Jim Bridenstine, Confirmed by Senate on Party-Line Vote|first=Kenneth|last=Chang|date=April 19, 2018|accessdate=April 19, 2018|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref> His nomination drew controversy given his lack of formal qualifications in science or engineering, and his previous rejection of the [[Scientific opinion on climate change|scientific consensus on climate change]].\n\n== Early life, education, and military service ==\nBridenstine was born in [[Ann Arbor, Michigan]] and is a [[Jenks High School]] graduate,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gtrnews.com/greater-tulsa-reporter/10894/jim-bridenstine-a-challenger-for-dist-1 |title=GTR Newspapers &#124; Find Local Tulsa, Bixby, Broken Arrow, Jenks, Union, and Owasso News, Sports, and Entertainment:Jim Bridenstine a Challenger for Dist. 1 |publisher=Gtrnews.com |date=April 24, 2012 |accessdate=July 5, 2012}}</ref> a graduate of [[Rice University]] with majors in Economics, Psychology, and Business, and has an [[MBA]] from [[Cornell University]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://restoringamericaproject.org/2012/04/24/jim-bridenstine/ |title=Jim Bridenstine |publisher=Restoring America Project |date=April 24, 2012 |accessdate=July 5, 2012 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120707203108/http://restoringamericaproject.org/2012/04/24/jim-bridenstine/ |archivedate=July 7, 2012}}</ref> He is a former executive director of the [[Tulsa Air and Space Museum]] & Planetarium and was a [[Naval Aviator]] in both the active duty [[United States Navy]] and the [[United States Naval Reserve]] where he flew the [[E-2C]] ''Hawkeye'' aircraft as part of a carrier air wing with the former and in Central and South America in support of the [[War on Drugs]] with the latter. In 2015, he transferred his Reserve commission and joined the [[Oklahoma Air National Guard]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.jimbridenstine.com/html/about.php |title=About Jim Bridenstine the Republican Patriot For U.S. Congress |publisher=Jimbridenstine.com |accessdate=July 5, 2012 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120622081715/http://jimbridenstine.com/html/about.php |archivedate=June 22, 2012}}</ref>{{primary inline|date=August 2015}} Bridenstine is an [[Eagle Scout (Boy Scouts of America)|Eagle Scout]]. As of 2016, Bridenstine is a State of Oklahoma record holder in the 200M long course freestyle relay.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.teamunify.com/czokslsc/UserFiles/File/Records%2017-18(1).pdf |title=Oklahoma Swimming Records |publisher=teamunify.com |page=6|date=April 9, 2016 |accessdate=May 2, 2016}}</ref>\n\n== U.S. House of Representatives ==\n[[File:Jim Bridenstine, official portrait, 113th Congress.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Bridenstine's official congressional portrait, 2013]]\n\n===Elections===\n==== 2012 ====\n{{see also|United States House of Representatives elections in Oklahoma, 2012#District 1}}\nIn the Republican primary election on June 26, 2012, Bridenstine defeated five-term incumbent U.S. Congressman [[John Sullivan (Oklahoma)|John Sullivan]] 54% to 46%.  Although he identified with the [[tea party movement|tea party]] and was perceived as running to Sullivan's right, Bridenstine's actual policy statements differed little from those of Sullivan.<ref>{{cite news |title=Tea Party favorite Bridenstine defeats incumbent Sullivan in Oklahoma House race|url=http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2012/06/27/tea-party-favorite-bridenstine-defeats-incumbent-sullivan-in-oklahoma-house/ |work=[[Fox News]] |date=June 27, 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.newson6.com/story/18889004/five-term-oklahoma-congressman-john-sullivan-suffers-primary-defeat |title=Five-Term Oklahoma Congressman Sullivan Suffers Primary Defeat|publisher=[[KOTV-DT|KOTV]] |date=June 26, 2012|accessdate=July 5, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Dan Phillips|url=http://www.ktul.com/story/18889029/bridenstine-defeats-incumbent-sullivan-in-primary |title=Bridenstine Defeats Incumbent Sullivan In Primary |publisher=[[KTUL]] |date=June 27, 2012 |accessdate=July 5, 2012}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite web|author=SEAN MURPHY, Associated Press |url=http://www.sfgate.com/news/article/Navy-pilot-upsets-5-term-Oklahoma-congressman-3665490.php |title=Navy pilot upsets 5-term Oklahoma congressman |publisher=SFGate |date=June 27, 2012 |accessdate=July 5, 2012}}</ref>{{update after|2012|12|15}} In the November 2012 general election, he defeated Democratic nominee John Olson 63%\u201332%, and won all five counties in the district.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=705054|title=Our Campaigns - OK - District 01 Race - Nov 06, 2012|website=www.ourcampaigns.com}}</ref>  Bridenstine had effectively clinched a seat in Congress by ousting Sullivan in the Republican primary. The 1st is a heavily Republican district with a [[Cook Partisan Voting Index]] of R+16, and has been in Republican hands since 1987. While in Congress Bridenstine joined the [[Freedom Caucus|House Freedom Caucus]] with other [[Conservatism in the United States|conservatives]].<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n==== 2014 ====\n{{see also|United States House of Representatives elections in Oklahoma, 2014#District 1}}\nBridenstine ran unopposed in the 2014 election.\n\n==== 2016 ====\n{{see also|United States House of Representatives elections in Oklahoma, 2016#District 1}}\nBridenstine retained his seat in the U.S. House of Representatives in the 2016 election.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2016/jun/28/oklahomas-gop-us-house-incumbents-looking-over-sho/|title=3 incumbent GOP state legislators lose primaries|last=Murphy|first=Sean|newspaper=The Washington Times|agency=AP|date=June 28, 2016|access-date=October 26, 2017}}</ref> Following the 2016 presidential election, Bridenstine was viewed as a possible candidate for either NASA administrator or Secretary of the Air Force under the [[Presidency of Donald Trump|Donald Trump administration]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://spacenews.com/nasa-administrator-bridenstine-his-names-in-the-mix-for-trumps-space-team/|title=NASA Administrator Bridenstine? His name's in the mix for Trump's space team|date=November 11, 2016|work=Space News|language=en-US|access-date=November 14, 2016}}</ref> Bridenstine had already declared that he would not run for re-election in 2018 after making a three-term pledge.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://newsok.com/article/5555627|title=Coburn will work to oust Mullin after congressman breaks term limit pledge |date=July 8, 2017|work=News OK|accessdate=April 1, 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Committee assignments ===\nBridenstine sat on the [[United States House Committee on Armed Services|Committee on Armed Services]] and [[United States House Committee on Science, Space and Technology|Committee on Science, Space and Technology]] during the [[113th Congress|113th]],<ref>[http://historycms.house.gov/WorkArea/DownloadAsset.aspx?id=15032414922 Official List of Standing Committee & Subcommittees for the 113th Congress].</ref> [[114th Congress|114th]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://historycms.house.gov/WorkArea/DownloadAsset.aspx?id=15032442531|title=Official Alphabetical List of Members with Committee Assignments for the 114th Congress |accessdate=April 19, 2018}}</ref> and [[115th Congress]]es.<ref>[http://clerk.house.gov/committee_info/oal.aspx Official alphabetical list of the House of Representatives of the United States One Hundred Fifteenth Congress] (September 1, 2017).</ref>\n\nWithin the Armed Services Committee, Bridenstine has sat on the [[United States House Armed Services Subcommittee on Seapower and Projection Forces|Subcommittee on Seapower and Projection Forces]]<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://armedservices.house.gov/subcommittees/seapower-projection-forces|title=Seapower and Projection Forces (114th Congress) |publisher=Armed Services Republicans|access-date=December 3, 2016}}</ref> and [[United States House Armed Services Subcommittee on Strategic Forces|Subcommittee on Strategic Forces]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://armedservices.house.gov/subcommittees/strategic-forces|title=Strategic Forces (114th Congress)|publisher=Armed Services Republicans|access-date=December 3, 2016}}</ref> Within the Science Committee, Bridenstine has sat on the [[United States House Science Subcommittee on Environment|Subcommittee on Environment]] (Chairman)<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://science.house.gov/subcommittees/subcommittee-environment-114th-congress|title=Subcommittee on Environment (114th Congress)|publisher=Committee on Science, Space, and Technology|access-date=December 3, 2016}}</ref> and [[United States House Science Subcommittee on Space|Subcommittee on Space]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://science.house.gov/subcommittees/subcommittee-space-114th-congress|title=Subcommittee on Space (114th Congress)|publisher=Committee on Science, Space, and Technology|access-date=December 3, 2016}}</ref> He is a member of the [[Freedom Caucus]]<ref name=\":5\">{{cite web|title=What is the House Freedom Caucus, and who's in it? |url=http://www.pewresearch.org/fact-tank/2015/10/20/house-freedom-caucus-what-is-it-and-whos-in-it/ |publisher=Pew research center|date=October 20, 2015|accessdate=October 26, 2017}}</ref> and the [[House Baltic Caucus]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Members |url=http://housebalticcaucus.webs.com/members|format=|publisher=House Baltic Caucus|date=|accessdate=February 21, 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Campaign financing ===\nIn the 2014 election cycle, Bridenstine's top campaign contributors were [[Northrop Grumman]], Latshaw Drilling, [[American Optometric Association]], [[Citizens United (organization)|Citizens United]] and the Every Republican is Crucial Political Action Committee.<ref name=\"crp\">{{cite web|url=http://www.opensecrets.org/politicians/contrib.php?cycle=2014&cid=N00033532&type=I&newmem=N|title=James Bridenstine top 20 Contributors, 2013-2014|date=May 28, 2015|publisher=The Center for Responsive Politics|accessdate=May 28, 2015}}</ref> \nHe received $29,000 from donors associated with the Turquoise Council of Americans and Eurasians and the [[Assembly of the Friends of Azerbaijan]] (AFAZ), per an analysis of the Center for Responsive Politics.<ref name=\"crp2\">{{cite web |url=http://www.opensecrets.org/politicians/contrib.php?cid=N00033532&cycle=2014&type=I&newMem=N&recs=100|title=James Bridenstine top 100 Contributors, 2013-2014|date=May 28, 2015|publisher=The Center for Responsive Politics|accessdate=May 28, 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Ethics investigation ===\nBridenstine's amendment to the defense appropriations bill came following a visit to [[Baku]] upon invitation of the [[SOCAR|State Oil Company of the Azerbaijan Republic]] for 10 members of Congress and 32 Staff members that became the subject of an ethics investigation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/investigations/10-members-of-congress-took-trip-secretly-funded-by-foreign-government/2015/05/13/76b55332-f720-11e4-9030-b4732caefe81_story.html|title=10 members of Congress took trip secretly funded by foreign government|website=Washington Post|access-date=December 2, 2016}}</ref> The members received numerous gifts during the trip totaling thousands of dollars in value. In 2013, Bridenstine returned two of the gifts (a pair of rugs worth several thousand dollars) back to the donor. He turned over remaining gifts received during the trip to the House Clerk in 2015, following a watchdog report that indicated that the source of the funding for the trip had not been properly declared. The OCE and House Ethics committee found that lawmakers and aides had no way of knowing that the trip was funded improperly.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://thehill.com/business-a-lobbying/business-a-lobbying/283682-lawmakers-turned-over-gifts-after-trip|title=Lawmakers turned over gifts after secretly funded trip to Azerbaijan|last=Dickson|first=Rebecca|date=June 16, 2016|newspaper=TheHill|access-date=September 7, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Ted Cruz campaign ===\nBridenstine was one of three co-chairs of the Veterans Coalition supporting [[Ted Cruz]] for the Republican nomination in the [[U.S. presidential election, 2016|2016 presidential campaign]]. He was joined in \"Vets for Ted\" by former [[U.S. Senator]] [[Bob Smith (American politician)|Bob Smith]] of [[New Hampshire]] and [[Texas State Senate|Texas State Senator]] [[Brian Birdwell]]. Bill Connor was national director of the coalition.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tedcruz.org/news/sen-cruz-names-u-s-sen-bob-smith-congressman-jim-bridenstine-and-texas-sen-brian-birdwell-co-chairs-of-vets-for-ted-bill-connor-to-serve-as-national-director/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150928223144/https://www.tedcruz.org/news/sen-cruz-names-u-s-sen-bob-smith-congressman-jim-bridenstine-and-texas-sen-brian-birdwell-co-chairs-of-vets-for-ted-bill-connor-to-serve-as-national-director/|dead-url=yes|archive-date=September 28, 2015|title=Sen. Cruz Names U.S. Sen. Bob Smith, Congressman Jim Bridenstine, and Texas Sen. Brian Birdwell Co-chairs of Vets for Ted; Bill Connor to Serve as National Director|publisher=tedcruz.org|accessdate=August 26, 2015}}</ref>\n\n== NASA administrator==\n[[File:Bridenstine Sworn In As NASA Administrator (NHQ201804230002).jpg|thumb|Bridenstine is sworn in as NASA's thirteenth administrator by Vice President Mike Pence.]]\n\n===Nomination===\nOn September 1, 2017, the White House announced that Bridenstine was President Donald Trump's preferred pick to head [[NASA]]. The choice was quickly criticized by both Republican and Democratic politicians, saying that NASA should be headed by a \"space professional\", not a politician or a Trump ally.<ref name=\":4\" /> Critics drew attention to Bridenstine's lack of formal qualifications in science or engineering (unlike previous appointees to that post).<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/09/02/science/jim-bridenstine-nasa-trump.html|title=Jim Bridenstine to Be Nominated by Trump to Lead NASA|last=Chang|first=Kenneth|date=September 2, 2017|work=The New York Times|access-date=September 3, 2017|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2017/09/14/politics/jim-bridenstine-nasa-opposition/index.html |title=Senators oppose Trump's pick to head NASA|last=CNN|first=Miranda Green,|work=CNN|access-date=September 14, 2017}}</ref> Florida Republican senator [[Marco Rubio]] said that Bridenstine's political history could prove controversial and delay the confirmation process, saying \"I just think it could be devastating for the space program\", while Democratic Senator [[Bill Nelson]], also of Florida and a former Payload Specialist for [[NASA]] who flew on [[STS-61-C]], said \"The head of NASA ought to be a space professional, not a politician.\"<ref name=\"NASA1\">Persio, Sofia Lotto [http://www.newsweek.com/trumps-nasa-chief-pick-jim-bridenstine-controversial-choice-658880 \"Why Donald Trump's NASA Chief Pick is a Controversial Choice\"], ''Newsweek'', September 2, 2017, Retrieved September 2, 2017</ref><ref name=\":3\" /> ''CNN'' found that Bridenstine's Facebook, YouTube and Twitter accounts were entirely deleted, while most of the interviews on his Soundcloud were deleted, at a time when Congress would be examining his record for his confirmation hearing.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/09/07/politics/kfile-bridenstine-nasa-online-presence/index.html|title=Parts of Trump NASA pick's online presence scrubbed|last=CNN|first=Andrew Kaczynski|website=CNN|access-date=September 9, 2017}}</ref>\n\nBridenstine has criticized NASA spending on [[Climatology|climate science]] and has supported increased privatization of U.S. civil and military space activities.<ref name=\":0\" /> According to ''NPR'', Bridenstine's [[Climate change denial|climate change denial views]] \"are sure to alarm scientists, because NASA conducts a huge amount of the global research on climate change.\"<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/thetwo-way/2017/09/04/548472775/trump-picks-oklahoma-congressman-to-head-nasa|title=Trump Picks Oklahoma Congressman To Head NASA|work=NPR.org|access-date=September 9, 2017|language=en}}</ref> NASA finds that climate-warming trends are \"extremely likely due to human activities\" and has written on its website that \"the small amount of dissent tends to come from a few vocal scientists who are not experts in the climate field or do not understand the scientific basis of long-term climate processes\".<ref name=\":2\"/>\n\nEric Stallmer, president of the [[Commercial Spaceflight Federation]], said he was \"very impressed with [Bridenstine's] deep knowledge of space technology issues and his record of strong leadership in promoting positive change.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://spacenews.com/bridenstine-faces-obstacles-to-senate-confirmation/|title=Bridenstine faces obstacles to Senate confirmation |last=Foust|first=Jeff|date=September 3, 2017|work=SpaceNews|access-date=September 4, 2017}}</ref> The decision to pick Bridenstine was also praised by Senator Ted Cruz.<ref name=\"Guarino\" />\n\nAccording to ''[[Science (magazine)|Science Magazine]]'', \"many expect that Bridenstine, who has written about the commercial potential of exploiting lunar resources, could shift the agency's emphasis [from its long-term mission of sending humans to Mars] toward the moon.\"<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.sciencemag.org/news/2017/09/trump-has-picked-politician-lead-nasa-good-thing|title=Trump has picked a politician to lead NASA. Is that a good thing?|date=September 1, 2017|work=Science {{!}} AAAS|access-date=September 9, 2017|language=en}}</ref> ''ABC News'' wrote that Bridenstine is in favor of both human missions to the Moon and Mars.<ref name=\":2\"/><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://arstechnica.com/science/2017/09/trumps-pick-for-nasa-lays-out-agenda-and-answers-critics/ |title=Trump's pick for NASA lays out agenda and answers critics|work=Ars Technica|access-date=September 20, 2017 |language=en-us}}</ref>\n\nThe U.S. Senate narrowly confirmed Bridenstine on April 19, 2018, by a party-line vote of 50\u201349.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Cama |first1=Timothy|title=Senate Confirms Trump's Pick to Lead NASA|url=http://thehill.com/policy/energy-environment/383950-senate-confirms-trumps-pick-to-lead-nasa|date=April 19, 2018|publisher=''[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]''|accessdate=April 21, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Chang|first1=Kenneth|title=Trump's NASA Nominee, Jim Bridenstine, Confirmed by Senate on Party-Line Vote |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/19/science/jim-bridenstine-nasa.html|date=April 19, 2018|publisher=''[[The New York Times]]'' |accessdate=April 21, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Andrews|first1=Natalie|last2=Pasztor|first2=Andy|title=Senate Confirms James Bridenstine to Lead NASA|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/senate-confirms-james-bridenstine-to-lead-nasa-1524166821 |date=April 19, 2018|publisher=''[[The Wall Street Journal]]''|accessdate=April 21, 2018}}</ref> He became the first member of Congress to lead NASA.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Technology/wireStory/trump-pick-head-nasa-faces-fight-climate-comments-49662994 |title=Trump pick to head NASA faces fight over climate comments|last=News|first=ABC|work=ABC News|access-date=September 9, 2017 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2018, Bridenstine stated:<blockquote>\u201cI don\u2019t deny the consensus, I believe fully in climate change and that we human beings are contributing to it in a major way\u201d<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wired.com/story/nasas-jim-bridenstine-agrees-humans-are-responsible-for-climate-change/ |title=NASA's Jim Bridenstine Agrees Humans Are Responsible for Climate Change |author=Eric Niiler |date=May 17, 2018 |website=Wired.com |publisher= |access-date=June 18, 2018}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n===Tenure===\nBridenstine was sworn in by Vice President [[Mike Pence]] at the [[NASA Headquarters]] building in [[Washington, D.C.]] on April 23, 2018.<ref>{{cite web | last1=Foust | first1=Jeff |title=Bridenstine Sworn in as NASA Administrator | url=http://spacenews.com/bridenstine-sworn-in-as-nasa-administrator/ | date=April 23, 2018 | publisher=''[[SpaceNews]]'' | accessdate=April 24, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last1=King | first1=Ledyard | title=After Bruising Nomination Fight, NASA Administrator James Bridenstine Facing More Challenges |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2018/04/23/after-bruising-nomination-fight-nasa-administrator-james-bridenstine-facing-more-challenges/542365002/ | date=April 23, 2018 |publisher=[[USA Today]] | accessdate=April 24, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last1=Harwood |first1=William |title=Jim Bridenstine Sworn in as NASA Administrator |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/nasa-administrator-jim-bridenstine-sworn-in/ | date=April 23, 2018 | publisher=[[CBS News]] |accessdate=April 24, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Political positions ==\n=== Space ===\nBridenstine has focused heavily on space policy during his tenure in Congress, stating \"[o]ur very way of life depends on space, the way we communicate, the way we navigate, the way we produce food and energy, the way we conduct banking.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-switch/wp/2016/04/12/why-congress-newest-space-advocate-says-the-u-s-faces-a-sputnik-moment/|title=Why Congress's newest space advocate says the U.S. faces a 'Sputnik moment'|website=Washington Post|access-date=December 2, 2016}}</ref> In April 2016 at the 32nd Annual Space Symposium, Bridenstine introduced H.R. 4945, the American Space Renaissance Act, comprehensive reform legislation with provisions affecting national security, civil, and commercial space policy.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://spacenews.com/bridenstine-introduces-american-space-renaissance-act/|title=Bridenstine introduces American Space Renaissance Act - SpaceNews.com|date=April 13, 2016|newspaper=SpaceNews.com|access-date=December 2, 2016|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nIn addition, Bridenstine has proposed legislation related to the regulatory process overseeing certain non-traditional space activities,<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite news|url=http://spacenews.com/proposed-legislation-would-close-commercial-space-regulatory-gap/ |title=Proposed legislation would close commercial space regulatory gap - SpaceNews.com|date=September 15, 2016 |newspaper=SpaceNews.com |access-date=December 2, 2016|language=en-US}}</ref> and helped secure funding for the Federal Aviation Administration's Office of Commercial Space Transportation.<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite news|url=http://spacenews.com/5-space-leaders-making-a-difference/|title=5 Space Leaders Making a Difference - SpaceNews.com|date=August 25, 2015|newspaper=SpaceNews.com|access-date=December 2, 2016 |language=en-US}}</ref> Recognizing his efforts, in 2015 SpaceNews named Bridenstine as one of five game changers in the world in space.<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\n=== Environment and climate ===\n\nBefore becoming the chief administrator of NASA, Bridenstine rejected the scientific consensus behind [[global climate change]]<ref name=\"NASA1\" /><ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\"Guarino\">Ben Guarino, [https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/speaking-of-science/wp/2017/09/05/trump-nominates-oklahoma-politician-and-climate-skeptic-to-run-nasa/ Trump nominates Oklahoma politician and climate skeptic to run NASA], ''Washington Post'' (September 5, 2017).</ref> and in a 2013 speech on the House floor stated that global temperatures stopped rising ten years earlier.<ref name=\"Guarino\"/> Bridenstine criticized the Obama administration for spending \"30 times as much money\" on climate science as on weather forecasting; [[PolitiFact]] said that assertion was \"mostly false\".<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.politifact.com/truth-o-meter/statements/2013/jun/14/jim-bridenstine/rep-jim-bridenstine-says-us-spends-30-times-much-c/|title=Jim Bridenstine: U.S. spends 30 times as much on climate change research as on weather forecasting|work=@politifact|access-date=September 9, 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\nBy May 2018, Bridenstine had reversed his position on climate change. At a town hall meeting in Washington D.C., Bridenstine stated that \"I fully believe and know that the climate is changing. I also know that we humans beings are contributing to it in a major way. Carbon dioxide is a greenhouse gas. We\u2019re putting it into the atmosphere in volumes that we haven\u2019t seen, and that greenhouse gas is warming the planet. That is absolutely happening, and we are responsible for it.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2018/05/trump-nasa-climate-change-bridenstine/560642/|title=Trump\u2019s NASA Chief: 'I Fully Believe and Know the Climate Is Changing'|last=Koren|first=Marina|work=The Atlantic|access-date=2018-05-20|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Bridenstine supported [[James Langevin]]'s legislation requiring the Defense Department to report on the effects of climate change on military installations and strategic battle plans.<ref>{{cite news|last=Welna|first=David|title=House Poised To Approve National Defense Authorization Bill|url=https://www.npr.org/2017/07/10/536505358/house-poised-to-approve-national-defense-authorization-bill|accessdate=November 5, 2017|work=NPR|date=July 10, 2017}}</ref> According to journalist [[Keith Cowing]], Bridenstine's support for the Langevin amendment \"was widely seen as being instrumental in its passage.\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Cowing |first1=Keith|title=Bridenstine's Climate Record Is Different Than You Thought|url=http://nasawatch.com/archives/2017/09/bridenstines-cl.html|website=NASA Watch|publisher=SpacRef Interactive|accessdate=November 5, 2017|date=September 15, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn the 114th Congress, he served as the Chairman of the Environment Subcommittee of the House Science, Space, and Technology Committee.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://science.house.gov/subcommittees/subcommittee-environment-114th-congress|title=Subcommittee on Environment (114th Congress)|newspaper=Committee on Science, Space, and Technology|access-date=December 2, 2016}}</ref> In that role, he has pushed the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration \"\u2026to integrate commercial data into its weather forecasting models.\"<ref name=\"auto1\" /> In September 2016, NOAA awarded two contracts to private weather satellite firms to provide data for its use.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://spacenews.com/two-companies-win-first-noaa-commercial-weather-contracts/|title=Two companies win first NOAA commercial weather contracts - SpaceNews.com|date=September 15, 2016|newspaper=SpaceNews.com|access-date=December 2, 2016|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.nasa.gov/about/highlights/bridenstine-biography.html NASA Administrator biography]\n* {{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/Oklahoma/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Jim_Bridenstine_%5BR-1%5D}}\n* {{C-SPAN|James Bridenstine}}\n* {{CongLinks |congbio=B001283 |votesmart=135894 |fec=H2OK01143 |congress=jim-bridenstine/2155}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{USRepSuccessionBox\n| state=Oklahoma\n| district=1\n| before=[[John Sullivan (Oklahoma)|John Sullivan]]\n| after=\n| reason=Vacant\n| years=2013\u20132018\n}}\n|-\n{{s-gov}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Charles Bolden]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of Administrators and Deputy Administrators of NASA|Administrator of the National Aeronautics and Space Administration]]|years=2018\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{NASAadmin}}\n{{OKRepresentatives}}\n{{Authority control}}\n